the  <i>Middelmore</i> which is recorded in the 13th and 15th centuries at Haughton in Morville (Shrops), though early bearers of the surname seem to be concentrated in Warwicks."],"variants":[{"name":"Millmore","meanings":["English: unexplained; probably a locative name from an unidentified minor place called  <i>Millmoor</i> or  <i>Middlemoor</i>. Compare the surname   Middlemore  , which is well recorded in Warwicks, the early bearers of which may provide some continuity with the 1501 bearer in Worcs cited below."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Dame Joan Middlemore was born in 1481, in Coventry, Warwickshire, England. She had at least 2 sons and 4 daughters with Julian Nethermill. She died in 1540, in her hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1481–1540":"1481–1540","1481–1539":"1481–1539","1508–1573":"1508–1573","1511–1547":"1511–1547","1513–1559":"1513–1559","1516–1560":"1516–1560","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1522–Female":"1522–Surnud","1513  (by 1515-19)":"1513","1560":"1560","1481":"1481","1547":"1547","about 1508":"umbes 1508","1513":"1513","1522":"1522","1511":"1511","1520":"1520","abt 1516":"umbes 1516","1540":"1540","1573":"1573","about 1511":"umbes 1511","about 1522":"umbes 1522","about 1520":"umbes 1520","1508":"1508","1539":"1539","1516":"1516","11 April 1539":"11. aprill 1539","1559":"1559","Coventry St Thomas, Warwickshire, England":"Coventry St Thomas, Warwickshire, England","Coventry, Warwickshire, England":"Coventry, Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"1481–1540":"1481–1540","1481–1539":"1481–1539","1508–1573":"1508–1573","1511–1547":"1511–1547","1513–1559":"1513–1559","1516–1560":"1516–1560","1520–Female":"1520–Kuollut","1522–Female":"1522–Kuollut","1513  (by 1515-19)":"1513","1560":"1560","1481":"1481","1547":"1547","about 1508":"noin 1508","1513":"1513","1522":"1522","1511":"1511","1520":"1520","abt 1516":"noin 1516","1540":"1540","1573":"1573","about 1511":"noin 1511","about 1522":"noin 1522","about 1520":"noin 1520","1508":"1508","1539":"1539","1516":"1516","11 April 1539":"11. huhtikuuta 1539","1559":"1559","Coventry St Thomas, Warwickshire, England":"Coventry St Thomas, Warwickshire, England","Coventry, Warwickshire, England":"Coventry, Warwickshire, England